For evaluating the proposed methodology for the actual detection of histamine, the standard curve was established based on the reactions with a series of histamine standards (0.1–100 ppm) (Fig. 4
                           ). For Hisp2, there is no obvious linear relationship between histamine concentration and carbon dots fluorescence intensity recovery. However, For Hisp1, Hisp3, and Hisp4 fluorescence intensity increased in the pace with histamine concentrations increase. Among them, Hisp3 possesses a tremendous linear relationship between the fluorescence intensity recovery (F–F0) and the logarithm value of histamine concentrations in the dynamic range from 0.1 to 100 ppm with the regression equation y = 484.01x-0.12 (Fig. 4c). The correlation coefficient of the calibration curve was 0.9966. The limit of detection (LOD = 3 N/S, where N is the standard deviation of the blank solution, and S is the slope of the calibration curve) was 21.15 ppb. When comparing the detection methods for histamine, the proposed methods demonstrate high sensitivity and selectivity (Table 1
                           ). Furthermore, the histamine was also detected using the NAC-CQDs/Hisp3 colorimetry system (Fig. S8). Whereas the fluorescence of NAC-CQDs was dramatically quenched after adding the peptide Hisp3, it was recovered according to the concentration of added histamine and clearly distinguished by naked eyes under the UV light.
